history.content:
EE 16B is definitely enough for EE137A/B. Just make sure you get your phasors/complex numbers basics down as you will start losing count of how many times you will be converting complex numbers between cartesian & polar forms. Knowing the basics of power factor and the power triangle might be useful too since the concept may seem unfamiliar at first but then it becomes fundamental/repeated throughout the rest of the course.

Someone else can chime in on EE130 but my impression from its syllabus is that it uses more physics/chemistry concepts like holes and electrons that should be self-contained within the course itself.
Is Math 54 + EE16B sufficient for EE classes like 130 or 137? If prerequisites are not enforced would this be fine or would I need to take EE47d too?
history.subject: Upper Div EE Requirements
